|
:INFO
Saddle Stitch by Hand
Thread a blunt harness needle on each end of a length of waxed thread equal to 3.5 times \
the seam length. Push the first needle through the first hole and center the thread. \
From there: first needle forward, second needle through the same hole crossing

:PATH
Finish Edges and Burnish
Bevel all exposed edges with an edge beveler, then dampen with water or gum
|
:INFO
Finish Edges and Burnish
Bevel all exposed edges with an edge beveler, then dampen with water or gum tragacanth. \
Rub a wood slicker or the back of a spoon along each edge using firm circular motion \
until the leather fibres compress into a smooth, rounded finish. Apply a thin

:QUOTE
Saddle stitch is slower than a machine and stronger than a machine. Every hole \
is a decision. That is what makes it worth doing by hand.

:NOTE
Tools Worth Buying Once
A good pricking iron and a sharp swivel knife are the two tools that separate \
clean work from frustrating work. Cheap pricking irons bend or space unevenly \
and make every stitch line look crooked. Spend more once on quality tools and \
the leather cost becomes the small part of the equation.

